<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="214" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,392]" pageId="11" pageNumber="214">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,260,285]" pageId="11" pageNumber="214">Remarks:</emphasis>
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Cao &amp; Yang &amp; Lin &amp; Zhang, 2018" authorityName="Cao &amp; Yang &amp; Lin &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2018" box="[657,752,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Anufrievia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curva" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[657,752,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="214">A. curva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[759,849,260,285]" pageId="11" pageNumber="214" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[759,849,260,285]" pageId="11" pageNumber="214">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but can be distinguished by the straight apex of the style, shorter apical processes of aedeagal shaft, and serrated apical margins of preatrial process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="214" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,392]" pageId="11" pageNumber="214">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,332,357]" pageId="11" pageNumber="214">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin word “ 
<emphasis box="[959,1038,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="214">fusinus</emphasis>
”, referring to the preatrial process being fusiform or spindle-shaped in ventral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
